    <!-- ============================================ -->
    <div class="section" id="controls">
        <div class="section-header">
            <div class="section-icon purple">‚öôÔ∏è</div>
            <h2>3. Internal Controls</h2>
        </div>

        <h3>3.1 Does Talkpush Test Its AI Internally?</h3>
        <p>
            <strong>Yes ‚Äî extensively.</strong> Every AI agent undergoes a rigorous, multi-stage testing process before being deployed to interact with real candidates. This process is not optional ‚Äî it is a mandatory part of every implementation.
        </p>

        <h3>3.2 Pre-Deployment Testing Process</h3>

        <div class="process-flow">
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <h5>Prompt Engineering</h5>
                <p>AI agent behavior is configured by a prompt engineer following established guidelines</p>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <h5>Manual QA</h5>
                <p>Internal team manually tests the agent multiple times, reviewing behavior and outputs</p>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <h5>AI Candidate Testing</h5>
                <p>100+ automated calls with diverse AI candidate profiles simulating different scenarios</p>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-num">4</div>
                <h5>Review &amp; Release</h5>
                <p>All test data analyzed; only released when all quality thresholds are met</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h4>AI Candidate Profiles for Testing</h4>
        <p>
            Talkpush has developed a library of <strong>AI candidate personas</strong>, each with distinct profiles designed to simulate real-world diversity:
        </p>
        <ul class="checklist">
            <li>Different language proficiency levels (A2 through C2)</li>
            <li>Different accents, dialects, and speech patterns</li>
            <li>Different demographic backgrounds and life situations</li>
            <li>Different behavioral styles (confident, nervous, hesitant, assertive)</li>
            <li>Edge cases: candidates who go off-topic, ask unexpected questions, express concerns about the AI format</li>
            <li>Adversarial scenarios: candidates who test the system's bias safeguards deliberately</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            By running <strong>100+ calls with these diverse profiles before release</strong>, we systematically identify and address issues that might only surface with specific candidate types. All results from these test calls are reviewed, and the AI agent is tuned and retested until it meets quality standards.
        </p>

        <div class="info-box blue">
            <h5>Implementation Note</h5>
            <p>The majority of issues are caught and resolved during this pre-deployment testing phase. By the time an AI agent is released to interact with real candidates, most potential problems have already been identified and eliminated. Bias-related issues that surface are <em>typically a pre-launch finding</em>, not something that commonly occurs in production.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>3.3 Are Models Validated Before Use?</h3>
        <p>
            Yes. Model validation is built into the deployment pipeline:
        </p>
        <ul class="checklist">
            <li><strong>Prompt validation:</strong> Every prompt is reviewed by the prompt engineering team before testing begins</li>
            <li><strong>Scoring validation:</strong> TalkScore outputs (CEFR levels, soft skill scores, attribute captures) are verified against expected results during QA</li>
            <li><strong>FAQ validation:</strong> All FAQ responses are tested for accuracy, completeness, and appropriateness before deployment</li>
            <li><strong>Behavioral validation:</strong> Agent tone, empathy, escalation handling, and conversation flow are tested across multiple scenarios</li>
            <li><strong>Bias validation:</strong> All 9 bias categories are explicitly tested during the pre-deployment phase</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>3.4 Is There Monitoring or QA to Catch Errors?</h3>
        <p>
            <strong>Yes ‚Äî and it is continuous, not periodic.</strong> Post-deployment monitoring includes:
        </p>

        <h4>Real-Time Call Analysis</h4>
        <p>Every single call is captured and analyzed automatically. The system evaluates each conversation against a comprehensive set of quality flags spanning three categories:</p>

        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Category</th>
                    <th>Number of Flags</th>
                    <th>What It Catches</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Agent Communication Quality</strong></td>
                    <td>13 flags</td>
                    <td>Intent misunderstanding, repetition, conversational loops, poor tone, hallucination, vague answers, abrupt endings, and more</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Bias &amp; Fairness</strong></td>
                    <td>9 flags</td>
                    <td>Gender, racial, age, socioeconomic, disability, cultural/nationality, language proficiency, accent/dialect, and interview format bias</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Candidate Behavior</strong></td>
                    <td>4 flags</td>
                    <td>Escalation requests, profanity, inappropriate content, privacy concerns</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h4>Alert System</h4>
        <p>
            The monitoring system is not passive ‚Äî it <strong>generates automatic alerts</strong> when issues are detected. The internal team has access to a dedicated dashboard showing:
        </p>
        <ul class="checklist">
            <li>All flagged calls with detailed breakdown of which flags were triggered</li>
            <li>Trending patterns that might indicate a systemic issue</li>
            <li>Information about missed captures or scoring errors</li>
            <li>Real-time visibility into call quality across all active AI agents</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Continuous Improvement Loop</h4>
        <p>
            When a flag is detected, it triggers a two-part response:
        </p>
        <div class="info-box green">
            <h5>1. Immediate Alert</h5>
            <p>The team is notified so the specific instance can be reviewed, and the candidate experience can be addressed if needed.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="info-box blue">
            <h5>2. Systematic Improvement</h5>
            <p>The AI agent's prompt is updated to prevent the same issue from recurring. This creates a system that gets more robust over time ‚Äî each detected issue makes the system better for all future candidates.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ============================================ -->
    <!-- SECTION 4: TALKSCORE SCORING METHODOLOGY      -->
    <!-- ============================================ -->
    <div class="section" id="cefr">
        <div class="section-header">
            <div class="section-icon orange">üìä</div>
            <h2>4. TalkScore Scoring ‚Äî Technical Methodology</h2>
        </div>

        <h3>4.1 How TalkScore Evaluates Spoken English</h3>
        <p>
            TalkScore evaluates spoken English across <strong>five key dimensions</strong> ‚Äî Pronunciation, Fluency, Grammar, Vocabulary, and Coherence ‚Äî using advanced speech recognition and machine learning models. The assessment happens <strong>passively during the conversational AI interview</strong>, meaning candidates do not take a separate language test. As they respond to interview questions, the AI simultaneously analyzes all aspects of their speech.
        </p>
        <p>
            The overall score maps to the <strong>band scale from 0 to 10</strong> (where 10 is expert, native-like speech), aligned with internationally recognized CEFR levels (A1‚ÄìC2) and IELTS-equivalent bands.
        </p>

        <div class="info-box green">
            <h5>Holistic AI Evaluation ‚Äî Not a Penalty System</h5>
            <p>TalkScore does <strong>NOT</strong> simply subtract a point for each mistake. It uses an AI-driven holistic evaluation trained on human examiners' ratings. A speaker who makes one or two small errors but uses complex sentences and good vocabulary may score higher than someone who makes no obvious errors but speaks only in very basic sentences. The scoring judges <strong>overall quality</strong>, not individual deductions.</p>
        </div>

        <h3>4.2 Evaluation Dimensions in Detail</h3>

        <!-- Pronunciation -->
        <div class="dimension-card">
            <h4>üîä Pronunciation (Pronunciation Quality)</h4>
            <p class="dim-desc">
                TalkScore evaluates pronunciation at the <strong>phoneme (individual sound) level and word level</strong> using acoustic models. For each word and syllable, it generates a <strong>quality score on a scale of 0 to 100</strong> that reflects pronunciation accuracy and intelligibility. The system compares the spoken audio against standard pronunciation models to assess how closely each sound matches expected patterns.
            </p>
            <ul class="tech-details">
                <li>Phoneme-level accuracy ‚Äî each individual sound is scored independently</li>
                <li>Word-level intelligibility ‚Äî how easily each word can be understood</li>
                <li>Quality score 0‚Äì100 per word/phoneme (90+ = native or near-native)</li>
                <li>Comparison against native speaker pronunciation models</li>
                <li>Accent is <strong>NOT penalized</strong> unless it affects intelligibility ‚Äî a thick accent with clear enunciation can still score well</li>
                <li>Multiple small issues collectively lower the score proportionally to their impact on understanding</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Fluency -->
        <div class="dimension-card blue-border">
            <h4>üó£Ô∏è Fluency (Speech Fluency)</h4>
            <p class="dim-desc">
                TalkScore measures fluency by examining the <strong>timing and flow of speech</strong>, computing various metrics directly from the audio signal. The system evaluates speech rate, pauses, hesitations, and run lengths to determine how smoothly a candidate communicates.
            </p>
            <ul class="tech-details">
                <li><strong>Speech rate</strong> ‚Äî syllables per second; natural pace is ideal (too slow or too fast both flag)</li>
                <li><strong>Pause detection</strong> ‚Äî total count, length, and distribution of silent and filled pauses ("um", "uh")</li>
                <li><strong>Mean pause duration</strong> ‚Äî average length of pauses throughout the response</li>
                <li><strong>Speech run length</strong> ‚Äî how many syllables spoken between pauses (longer runs = more fluent)</li>
                <li><strong>Non-speech sounds</strong> ‚Äî repetitions, self-corrections, nervous fillers captured</li>
                <li>No fixed point deduction per pause ‚Äî metrics are compared against typical fluent speaker profiles via ML models</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Grammar -->
        <div class="dimension-card purple-border">
            <h4>üìù Grammar (Grammar Quality)</h4>
            <p class="dim-desc">
                TalkScore transcribes speech and applies a specialized <strong>grammar analysis model trained on hundreds of speech samples</strong> to assess both grammatical <strong>accuracy</strong> and grammatical <strong>range</strong>. Unlike a basic grammar checker, it evaluates the sophistication and variety of sentence structures alongside error detection.
            </p>
            <ul class="tech-details">
                <li><strong>Grammatical accuracy</strong> ‚Äî identifies errors (verb tense, subject-verb agreement, articles, word order) with categorized feedback</li>
                <li><strong>Grammatical range &amp; complexity</strong> ‚Äî evaluates sentence variety, subordinate clauses, verb tense diversity, noun phrase complexity</li>
                <li><strong>Response length</strong> ‚Äî checks if the candidate spoke enough to demonstrate grammar proficiency</li>
                <li>Categorized error feedback with corrections (e.g., "STYLE", "GRAMMAR" categories)</li>
                <li>Perfectly error-free but very simple sentences may <strong>not</strong> score as high as complex sentences with minor errors</li>
                <li>AI model trained on human-rated samples to correlate features with expert grammar ratings</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Vocabulary -->
        <div class="dimension-card orange-border">
            <h4>üìñ Vocabulary (Lexical Resource)</h4>
            <p class="dim-desc">
                TalkScore examines the transcript for <strong>variety and sophistication of word choice</strong> using multiple sub-metrics. It goes beyond counting "big words" to evaluate the overall level of word choice ‚Äî range, appropriateness, and complexity.
            </p>
            <ul class="tech-details">
                <li><strong>Lexical diversity</strong> ‚Äî how many different words are used (vs. repeating simple words)</li>
                <li><strong>Word sophistication</strong> ‚Äî use of advanced, less common, or domain-specific terms</li>
                <li><strong>Word specificity</strong> ‚Äî precision of word choice (e.g., "consumer electronics" vs. "things")</li>
                <li><strong>Collocations &amp; idioms</strong> ‚Äî use of natural word combinations and figurative language</li>
                <li><strong>Academic/formal language</strong> ‚Äî appropriate use of formal vocabulary when context requires it</li>
                <li>Reference lexicon and frequency lists determine which words are basic vs. advanced</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Coherence -->
        <div class="dimension-card red-border">
            <h4>üîó Coherence (Organization &amp; Structure)</h4>
            <p class="dim-desc">
                TalkScore evaluates how well responses are organized and how ideas are <strong>connected together</strong>, making them easy to follow. The system parses the transcript to identify linking words, logical structure, and discourse-level quality.
            </p>
            <ul class="tech-details">
                <li><strong>Connective variety</strong> ‚Äî use of basic (and, but), causal (because, therefore), and contrast (however, on the other hand) connectives</li>
                <li><strong>Lexical density</strong> ‚Äî proportion of content words vs. function words (balanced density is ideal)</li>
                <li><strong>Pronoun usage</strong> ‚Äî checks that pronouns have clear references and are not overused</li>
                <li><strong>Verb &amp; adverb diversity</strong> ‚Äî variety in descriptive language (e.g., "increase, surge, decline" vs. only "go up")</li>
                <li><strong>Logical flow</strong> ‚Äî whether ideas follow a clear structure without abrupt topic jumps</li>
                <li>Metrics calibrated against typical responses at various proficiency levels</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>4.3 Overall Score Calculation</h3>
        <p>
            The Overall Score is a <strong>composite evaluation</strong> derived from all five dimensions. It is <strong>not a simple average or sum</strong> ‚Äî it uses machine learning models trained on human examiners' ratings to predict a score that correlates with what a professional examiner would give.
        </p>

        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Scoring Principle</th>
                    <th>How It Works</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Holistic, not additive</strong></td>
                    <td>The score is not "start at 10 and subtract per error." It evaluates overall quality across all dimensions simultaneously.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Severity-aware</strong></td>
                    <td>One minor mispronunciation barely dents the score; many issues or very basic language will lower it significantly.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Complexity rewarded</strong></td>
                    <td>In grammar, a few errors offset by strong complex structures may score higher than perfect but simplistic sentences.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Accent-neutral</strong></td>
                    <td>Having an accent is NOT penalized unless it causes mispronunciations or reduces intelligibility. A thick accent with clear enunciation can score well.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Context-sensitive</strong></td>
                    <td>Each component's impact depends on its severity and the overall context of the response, not fixed weightings.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Trained on human ratings</strong></td>
                    <td>The algorithm learned to predict scores by studying how human examiners rate large datasets of native and non-native speakers.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>4.4 CEFR Alignment</h3>
        <p>
            TalkScore's overall scoring is aligned with established standards. The 0‚Äì10 band scale maps to <strong>CEFR levels (A1‚ÄìC2)</strong> and IELTS-equivalent bands, providing internationally recognized proficiency benchmarks:
        </p>

        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Band Range</th>
                    <th>CEFR Level</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>0 ‚Äì 2</strong></td>
                    <td>A1 ‚Äì A2</td>
                    <td>Beginner to Elementary ‚Äî very limited spoken communication</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>3 ‚Äì 4</strong></td>
                    <td>B1</td>
                    <td>Intermediate ‚Äî can handle basic conversational topics with noticeable limitations</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>5 ‚Äì 6</strong></td>
                    <td>B2</td>
                    <td>Upper-Intermediate ‚Äî competent communicator with some errors, typical minimum for professional roles</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>7 ‚Äì 8</strong></td>
                    <td>C1</td>
                    <td>Advanced ‚Äî effective, fluent communication with occasional minor issues</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>9 ‚Äì 10</strong></td>
                    <td>C2</td>
                    <td>Proficiency ‚Äî near-native, expert-level spoken English across all dimensions</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>4.5 Technical Summary</h3>
        <p>At a high level, TalkScore works as an <strong>automated speaking examiner</strong>:</p>

        <div class="process-flow">
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <h5>Capture</h5>
                <p>Speech audio is captured during the AI interview conversation</p>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <h5>Transcribe</h5>
                <p>Advanced speech recognition converts audio to text with timing data</p>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <h5>Analyze</h5>
                <p>ML models evaluate pronunciation, fluency, grammar, vocabulary, and coherence</p>
            </div>
            <div class="process-step">
                <div class="step-num">4</div>
                <h5>Score</h5>
                <p>Holistic AI-driven scoring produces band scores aligned to CEFR/IELTS</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="info-box orange">
            <h5>Key Technical Differentiator</h5>
            <p>TalkScore's scoring mimics a human evaluator's holistic approach rather than tallying mistakes. The system uses ML models trained on large datasets of non-native and native speakers to evaluate how <em>intelligible</em>, <em>natural</em>, and <em>rich</em> the speech is. Issues in any dimension will lower scores, but the impact depends on severity and overall context ‚Äî exactly as a human examiner would judge.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ============================================ -->
    <!-- SECTION 5: ASSESSMENT INTEGRITY                -->
    <!-- ============================================ -->
    <div class="section" id="research">
        <div class="section-header">
            <div class="section-icon purple">üî¨</div>
            <h2>5. Assessment Integrity &amp; Compliance</h2>
        </div>

        <h3>5.1 Assessment Integrity Guarantees</h3>
        <p>Based on TalkScore's architecture and our monitoring framework, the platform provides the following assessment integrity guarantees:</p>

        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Guarantee</th>
                    <th>How It's Ensured</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Independent scoring dimensions</strong></td>
                    <td>Language and soft skill assessments use separate, dedicated AI models ‚Äî one does not influence the other</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>No proxy-based scoring</strong></td>
                    <td>The AI does not infer soft skills from language scores or vice versa</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Consistent evaluation criteria</strong></td>
                    <td>Every candidate is assessed against the same standards ‚Äî no interviewer variability</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Real-time bias monitoring</strong></td>
                    <td>9 bias categories checked on every call with automatic alerts</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Comprehensive QA before deployment</strong></td>
                    <td>100+ test calls with diverse AI candidate profiles before any real candidate interaction</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Full auditability</strong></td>
                    <td>Every call recorded, transcribed, and analyzable ‚Äî complete audit trail</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Continuous improvement</strong></td>
                    <td>Flagged issues trigger prompt improvements, making the system more robust over time</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Trained on human judgment</strong></td>
                    <td>Scoring models were trained on ratings from professional human examiners, ensuring alignment with expert evaluation standards</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>5.2 Data Privacy and Compliance</h3>
        <p>All candidate data collected through TalkScore AI interviews is handled in accordance with applicable data protection regulations. Candidates are informed that their interview is AI-powered, and privacy concerns raised during calls are flagged through the <code>privacy_concern_raised</code> monitoring flag, ensuring prompt and appropriate response.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- ============================================ -->
    <!-- CLOSING                                       -->
